Introduction

According to Hirschfeld (2001), out of all adults that visit physicians with anxiety and depression, more than 50% of these individuals also have a second anxiety or depression disorder showing that these two emotional disorders are highly comorbid. Across the world, around 359 million people live with anxiety disorders and 280 million live with depression (World Health Organization, 2025). These highly common disorders affect millions of people in their daily lives making it important to identify common issues that can cause these disorders.

Using a dataset on tech use and stress wellness, this project seeks to identify what features are the most important in predicting depression and anxiety. As anxiety and depression are highly co-morbid, this project also seeks to identify whether the features that are important for anxiety and depression overlap.

The questions this project asks are:

  1. What features are the most important for predicting anxiety?
  2. What features are the most important for predicting depression?
  3. Do the features that are the most important for predicting depression overlap with the features that are most important for predicting anxiety?

Citations:

  • Hirschfeld, R. M. A. (2001). The Comorbidity of Major Depression and Anxiety Disorders: Recognition and Management in Primary Care. The Primary Care Companion to the Journal of Clinical Psychiatry, 3(6), 244-254. DOI: 10.4088/pcc.v03n0609.

  • World Health Organization (2025). Mental Disorders. https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/mental-disorders

Data Curation

We began our data curration by searching for a dataset that outlines many features related to mental health and what causes both anxiety and depression. We found this data set on Kaggle that outlines many features related to mental health and technology use:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nagpalprabhavalkar/tech-use-and-stress-wellness/data

We chose this set because we wanted to gain insights on the comorbidity of anxiety and depression and how tech use affects these conditions in people of different ages. We hypothesized that anxiety and depression are comorbid, meaning they may be caused by the presence or lack of the same features. We also hypothesized that younger generations' mental health are more affected by screen time, and doing exploratory data analysis on this set will allow us to test this hypothesis. This dataset has information about many aspects of one's lifestyle choices and how they impact mental health which we can use to draw conclusions about how they are related.

We evaluated the features of the dataset by organizing the dataset CSV into a readable DataFrame and cleaning the data using Pandas. We then chose the most relevant features of the dataset to conduct our initial exploratory data analysis. These key features included age, location, anxiety score, social media hours, etc.

Statistical Conclusions

Hypothesis Test 1: ANOVA

The Ho for the ANOVA test for mental health score by location is "there is no relationship between location and mental health score." The Ha is "there is a relationship between location and mental health score."

In[]:
# ANOVA test for mental health score by location (urban, suburban, rural)
grouped = tech_and_stress_df.groupby('location_type')
urban = grouped.get_group('Urban')["mental_health_score"]
suburban = grouped.get_group('Suburban')["mental_health_score"]
rural = grouped.get_group('Rural')["mental_health_score"]
stat, p = stats.f_oneway(urban, suburban, rural)
print(stat, p)

2.1434958440945886 0.11735204819958318

Because the p value (0.11735) is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the Ho. Meaning, that there is a relationship between location and mental health score.

In[]:
# Tukey post-hoc tests for each region
urban_suburban = stats.tukey_hsd(urban, suburban)
urban_rural = stats.tukey_hsd(urban, rural)
rural_suburban = stats.tukey_hsd(rural, suburban)
print(urban_suburban, urban_rural, rural_suburban)

Hypothesis test 2: Correlation

In[]:
# Hypothesis 2: correlation between weekly anxiety score and social media hours
anxiety_data = tech_and_stress_df['weekly_anxiety_score']
sm_data = tech_and_stress_df['social_media_hours']
correlation = anxiety_data.corr(sm_data)
print("Pearson's Correlation Coefficient: ", correlation)
tech_and_stress_df.plot.scatter(x='weekly_anxiety_score', y='social_media_hours', color='hotpink')
plt.title("Weekly Anxiety Score vs. Social Media Hours")

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient:  0.8089892624587282
Out[]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Weekly Anxiety Score vs. Social Media Hours')

Hypothesis #2: Analysis

Ho = There is no correlation between weekly anxiety score and social media hours.

Ha = There is a signfiicant correlation between weekly anxiety score and social media hours.

The pearson's correlation coefficient between weekly anxiety score and social media hours is r=0.81. This means there is a relatively strong, positive correlation between the two variables. The p-value is < 0.01. Because the p-value is extremely close to 0.0 and less than the alpha value of 0.05, we can conlcude that this correlation is signficiant and reject the null hypothesis that there is no correlation between weekly anxiety score and social media hours.

Statisical Test 3: outliers/boxplot

In[]:
data = tech_and_stress_df.dropna(subset=['daily_screen_time_hours', 'gender'])

# Boxplot to visualize outliers
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='daily_screen_time_hours', data=data, palette='Set2')
plt.title("Daily Screen Time by Gender")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Daily Screen Time (hours)")
plt.show()

# KruskalWallis test (nonparametric, robust to outliers)
groups = [group["daily_screen_time_hours"].values for name, group in data.groupby("gender")]
stat, p = stats.kruskal(*groups)

print(f"Kruskal-Wallis H-statistic: {stat:.3f}, p-value: {p:.4f}")
if p < 0.05:
    print("Reject H  Significant difference in daily screen time between genders.")
else:
    print("Fail to reject H  No significant difference between genders.")

Primary Analysis and Visualization

In order to predict anxiety and depression, we employed multiple linear regression to predict these values. We used multiple regression because we wanted to use multiple features of the dataset to predict continuous values. To prepare our data for linear regression, we converted boolean to numeric values and categorical values to numeric values using label encoding. We dropped columns we thought wouldnt be relevant to our analysis such as user_id, age, and gender. We also dropped mental health score as we believed it would we be to similar to depression and anxiety so we chose not to include it.

In[]:
# Depression linear regression
# Change bool columns to type int
tech_and_stress_df['uses_wellness_apps'] = tech_and_stress_df['uses_wellness_apps'].astype(int)
tech_and_stress_df['eats_healthy'] = tech_and_stress_df['eats_healthy'].astype(int)

# Change location type to numeric (label encoding)
le = LabelEncoder()
tech_and_stress_df['location_type'] = le.fit_transform(tech_and_stress_df['location_type'])

# Depression (using linear regression + RFE)
# X = everything but id, age, gender, and mental health score (too similar)
# y = depression score

X = tech_and_stress_df.drop(['user_id', 'age', 'gender', 'mental_health_score'], axis=1)

X_depression = X.drop(['weekly_depression_score'], axis=1)
y_depression = X['weekly_depression_score']

# Standardize Data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_depression, y_depression, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

scaler_X = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler_X.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled  = scaler_X.transform(X_test)

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

model_diff = pd.DataFrame({'Depression actual value': y_test,'Depression predicted value': y_test_pred})
display(model_diff)

mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
r2 = metrics.r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

print('Mean Absolute Error:', mae)
print('Mean Square Error:', mse)
print('Root Mean Square Error:', r2)

After training a linear regression model for depression, the R2 score was 0.63 showing that 63% of the variance of depression scores can be explained through multiple linear regression.

In order to answer our questions looking at what features are the most important for predicting depression and anxiety, we used Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE), which works by recursively eliminating the least important features based on model performance. We chose to look at the top 5 most important features.

In[]:
# Depression RFE
# Define the base model
model = LinearRegression()

# Apply RFE
rfe = RFE(estimator=model, n_features_to_select=5)
rfe.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Predict and evaluate
y_pred = rfe.predict(X_test_scaled)
display("Selected features:", list(X_depression.columns[rfe.support_]))
display("R2 on test:", r2_score(y_test, y_pred))

# Build correlation matrix for selected features
heatmap = tech_and_stress_df[['weekly_depression_score'] + list(X_depression.columns[rfe.support_])]
corr = heatmap.corr()

# Clustermap
sns.clustermap(
    corr,
    annot=True,
    cmap="PiYG",
    linewidths=.5,
    figsize=(8, 6)
)

Our third question asked if the features that are the most important for predicting depression overlap with the features that are most important for predicting anxiety. Based on the previous results, social media usage and stress level were both some of the most important features for predicting anxiety and depression with stress level being the most highly correlated feature for both anxiety and depression. This matches with previous research showing that anxiety and depression are comorbid as based on the machine learning analysis they have some overlapping features.

Insights and Conlusions

After reading through the project, an uninformed reader will know the lifestyle factors that are most likely to affect depression and anxiety, as well as the ages that are most impacted by poor mental health. A reader who already knew the topic would learn that the lifestyle factors that affect depression and anxiety are similar, and decrease overall mental health.

Based on our observations from our models and analysis we can conclude that the ages with the highest technology used are 20-30 year olds, higher technology usage leads to lower anxiety and depression scores, and higher physical activity leads to lower anxiety and depression scores. From our data visualization we see that the 20-30 year olds have the highest social media usage hours and overall daily screen time hours. Additionally, we see that higher social media usage and higher daily screen time leads to a lower depression and anxiety score. This means that the more people overuse technology, specifically social media, the more their mental health declines. We can also conclude that since 20-30 year olds use technology more, they are more susceptible to depression and anxiety. We observe that depression and anxiety score decrease as mindfulness minutes and physical activity increases. From the observation we can conclude that people that spend less time on social media, and more time taking care of their mental and physical health are less likely to suffer from depression and anxiety.

Overall, we can use this data and analysis to inform people, especially 20-30 year olds, about how their lifestyle choices affect their mental health. Educating them will help improve their quality of life, and help them form habits that will lead to a healthier life. Utilizing our Linear Regression Model and Regression Feature Estimation we have been able to predict what the anxiety and depression scores will be, as well as the features that affect it the most.
